[3] Research: Novel CoV detected in patients' stool
[a]
Date: Sat 1 Feb 2020
Source: Szddy [edited]
http://www.szdsyy.com/News/9f79408f-bc55-4ab6-9a72-835b70d4e3ff.html


On the evening of 1 Feb 2020, according to the Shenzhen Third People's Hospital, the Institute of Liver Disease Research of the hospital found that 2019-nCoV nucleic acid (new coronavirus) was positive in the stools of certain patients with pneumonia diagnosed with the new coronavirus. It is likely to indicate the presence of live virus in the stool.

According to researchers at Shenzhen Third People's Hospital, researchers are currently conducting research on further virus isolation. Citizens are reminded to wash their hands frequently while wearing a mask and to pay attention to personal hygiene.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Kunihiko Iizuka

***
[b]
Date: Sun 2 Feb 2020
Source: CCTV News [edited]
http://www.chinanews.com/gn/2020/02-02/9076366.shtml


Recently, some media reported that the stool of patients with confirmed new-type coronavirus pneumonia in Shenzhen was positive for nucleic acid in stool, and the virus is at risk of fecal-oral transmission.

Academician Yi Zhongnanshan pointed out in an interview with CCTV reporters on this issue that some patients' fecal nucleic acid test is a fact and should be paid close attention to. If the virus is really isolated, the possibility of fecal-oral transmission increases.

What is the difference between nucleic acid isolation and virus isolation?

Zhong Zhongshan: Isolating a virus means that there is a live virus, and a nucleic acid is a nucleic acid. If the virus is isolated, it means that there is a coronavirus in the stool, then the problem is even greater.

Isolated nucleic acid does not mean there is a virus, does it?

Zhong Zhongshan: These are 2 concepts. Nucleic acid is a sequence of (virus), suggesting that it may be, but the actual isolation of live virus is another matter.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Kunihiko Iizuka

